21
00:03:40,304 --> 00:03:45,101
STALKER

22
00:03:45,684 --> 00:03:48,104
"Was it a meteorite
or a visitation from outer space?

23
00:03:48,187 --> 00:03:52,900
Whatever it was, in our small country,
there appeared a miracle — the Zone.

24
00:03:52,983 --> 00:03:57,279
We sent in troops. Not one returned.

25
00:03:57,363 --> 00:04:03,202
Then we surrounded the Zone
with a security cordon.

26
00:04:03,285 --> 00:04:05,246
We did right...

27
00:04:05,329 --> 00:04:09,792
Although I'm not sure. I'm not sure."

28
00:04:09,875 --> 00:04:14,630
From an interview with Nobel Prize winner
Professor Wallace to an RAI correspondent.

29
00:10:19,787 --> 00:10:21,538
Why did you take my watch?

30
00:10:25,042 --> 00:10:27,503
Where are you going?

31
00:10:30,881 --> 00:10:35,302
You gave me your word. | believed you.

32
00:10:39,890 --> 00:10:42,518
You won't think of yourself.
But what about us?

33
00:10:44,269 --> 00:10:46,271
Think about your daughter.

34
00:10:48,524 --> 00:10:52,402
She's not even used to you yet,
and you're going back to your old ways.

35
00:10:56,824 --> 00:11:00,744
You've turned me into an old hag,
ruined my life.

36
00:11:01,119 --> 00:11:03,831
Quiet. You'll wake up Monkey.

37
00:11:05,582 --> 00:11:08,877
| can't spend my life waiting for you.
Il die.

38
00:11:23,225 --> 00:11:25,185
You were going to get proper work.

39
00:11:26,854 --> 00:11:29,606
They promised you a decent, normal job.

40
00:11:33,944 --> 00:11:35,696
I'll be back soon.

41
00:11:37,322 --> 00:11:39,199
You'll be back in prison.

42
00:11:39,575 --> 00:11:42,160
Next time, they'll give you ten years
instead of five.

43
00:11:42,452 --> 00:11:44,830
And you'll have nothing to show
for those ten years.

44
00:11:44,913 --> 00:11:46,832
Not the Zone, not anything.

45
00:11:47,749 --> 00:11:51,545
And in ten years, I'll be dead.

46
00:11:53,630 --> 00:11:57,134
"Prison"? I'm imprisoned everywhere.

47
00:12:01,138 --> 00:12:03,932
Let me go.
- | won't let you go.

48
00:12:04,016 --> 00:12:05,517
- Let me go.
- | won't!

49
00:12:15,485 --> 00:12:16,945
Go on, then!

50
00:12:18,155 --> 00:12:19,990
And may you rot there!

51
00:12:21,325 --> 00:12:25,162
| curse the day | met you, you scum!

52
00:12:26,204 --> 00:12:29,917
God cursed you by sending you that child.

53
00:12:31,001 --> 00:12:34,171
And he cursed me because of you.
You bastard!

54
00:13:20,592 --> 00:13:24,471
My dear, the world
is so unutterably boring.

55
00:13:24,554 --> 00:13:29,059
There's no telepathy, no ghosts,
no flying saucers.

56
00:13:29,142 --> 00:13:31,228
They can't exist.

57
00:13:31,895 --> 00:13:34,523
The world is ruled by cast-iron laws.

58
00:13:34,606 --> 00:13:39,152
These laws are not broken.

59
00:13:39,236 --> 00:13:41,321
They just can't be broken.

60
00:13:43,490 --> 00:13:47,452
Don't hope for flying saucers.
That would be too interesting.

61
00:13:48,245 --> 00:13:50,080
But what about the Bermuda Triangle?

62
00:13:50,372 --> 00:13:53,834
You're not going to contradict...
- Yes, | am.

63
00:13:53,917 --> 00:13:56,253
There is no Bermuda Triangle.

64
00:13:56,336 --> 00:13:57,796
There's Triangle ABC,

65
00:13:57,879 --> 00:14:01,466
which equals
Triangle A prime, B prime, C prime.

66
00:14:01,800 --> 00:14:05,387
It's all so tedious, so very tedious.

67
00:14:06,555 --> 00:14:09,516
In the Middle Ages, life was interesting.

68
00:14:09,599 --> 00:14:14,146
Every house had its goblin,
each church had God.

69
00:14:14,229 --> 00:14:18,400
People were young.
Now every fourth person is old.

70
00:14:18,483 --> 00:14:21,528
It's boring, my angel. It's so boring.

71
00:14:21,611 --> 00:14:26,825
But you said that the Zone is the product
of a super civilization —

72
00:14:26,908 --> 00:14:32,164
Which is probably also boring,
also with laws and triangles,

73
00:14:32,247 --> 00:14:35,917
but without goblins
and, of course, without any God.

74
00:14:37,252 --> 00:14:41,673
Because if there is a God,
he'll be that very triangle.

75
00:14:42,716 --> 00:14:45,010
Then | simply don't know.

76
00:14:48,680 --> 00:14:52,476
It's for me. Good-bye, dear friend.

77
00:14:55,270 --> 00:14:58,398
This fine lady agreed
to go with us into the Zone.

78
00:14:58,482 --> 00:15:01,485
She's so brave. Her name is —

79
00:15:02,486 --> 00:15:04,780
Excuse me, what is your name?

80
00:15:04,863 --> 00:15:07,449
Are you really a stalker?

81
00:15:14,164 --> 00:15:16,166
I'll explain everything later.

82
00:15:24,966 --> 00:15:26,343
Get lost.

83
00:15:34,768 --> 00:15:36,353
An idiot.

84
00:15:40,690 --> 00:15:43,026
So you've been drinking?

85
00:15:43,110 --> 00:15:49,116
| simply had a drink,
as does half of all humanity.

86
00:15:49,199 --> 00:15:53,662
And the other half also gets drunk,
including women and children.

87
00:15:54,162 --> 00:15:55,664
| simply had a drink.

88
00:16:17,769 --> 00:16:19,980
Damn it! Someone spilled something.

89
00:16:34,244 --> 00:16:36,079
Drink. It's still early.

90
00:16:39,082 --> 00:16:42,252
How about one for the road?

91
00:16:44,421 --> 00:16:45,922
What do you think?

92
00:17:00,478 --> 00:17:05,192
- Take it away.
- Of course, the prohibition law.

93
00:17:05,275 --> 00:17:07,694
"Alcohol is the scourge of mankind."

94
00:17:07,777 --> 00:17:09,321
Let's drink beer then.

95
00:17:12,324 --> 00:17:13,783
Is he coming with us?

96
00:17:14,910 --> 00:17:18,622
Don't worry. He'll sober up.
He needs to go there, too.

97
00:17:26,504 --> 00:17:30,967
- Are you really a professor?
- If you wish.

98
00:17:31,343 --> 00:17:35,722
In that case, let me introduce myself.
My name is —

99
00:17:35,805 --> 00:17:38,391
They call him the Writer.

100
00:17:38,475 --> 00:17:40,393
And what's my name?

101
00:17:40,936 --> 00:17:43,230
You're the professor.

102
00:17:44,606 --> 00:17:46,107
Of course.

103
00:17:46,816 --> 00:17:50,445
I'm a writer, so naturally
everyone calls me the Writer.

104
00:17:51,238 --> 00:17:55,033
- What do you write about?
- About my readers.

105
00:17:55,116 --> 00:17:57,494
No sense in writing about anything else.

106
00:17:57,577 --> 00:18:00,872
There's no sense
in writing about anything.

107
00:18:01,873 --> 00:18:05,877
What are you? A chemist?

108
00:18:07,003 --> 00:18:08,838
I'd say a physicist.

109
00:18:08,922 --> 00:18:12,175
That's probably tedious, too.
Searching for the truth.

110
00:18:13,551 --> 00:18:18,265
You dig here and there.

111
00:18:18,348 --> 00:18:22,435
Right. The nucleus consists of protons.

112
00:18:22,519 --> 00:18:24,604
That's a good dig.

113
00:18:24,688 --> 00:18:28,942
Triangle ABC
equals Triangle A prime, B prime, C prime.

114
00:18:29,526 --> 00:18:31,611
But with me, it's a different matter.

115
00:18:32,654 --> 00:18:38,034
| dig for the truth, but, while | do,
something happens to it.

116
00:18:38,535 --> 00:18:42,664
The truth changes into a pile of —

117
00:18:43,665 --> 00:18:45,250
| won't say what.

118
00:18:51,131 --> 00:18:53,258
It's just fine for you.

119
00:18:53,341 --> 00:18:56,803
Say there's some antique pot in a museum.

120
00:18:56,886 --> 00:18:59,597
In its own time, it was a trash bin.

121
00:18:59,681 --> 00:19:06,646
But now it draws admiration for
its simplicity of line and unique form.

122
00:19:07,397 --> 00:19:10,608
And everyone oohs and aahs over it.

123
00:19:10,692 --> 00:19:14,988
Suddenly, it turns out
not to be an antique at all.

124
00:19:15,071 --> 00:19:19,075
It was planted by some joker for a laugh.

125
00:19:20,076 --> 00:19:25,915
The sounds of admiration die away.
Some connoisseurs!

126
00:19:26,249 --> 00:19:28,835
This is what you think about all the time?

127
00:19:31,004 --> 00:19:33,131
God forbid.

128
00:19:33,214 --> 00:19:36,092
| seldom think. It's bad for me.

129
00:19:36,176 --> 00:19:41,014
It's impossible to write and keep
thinking about success or failure.

130
00:19:41,097 --> 00:19:42,474
Naturlich.

131
00:19:42,557 --> 00:19:46,644
But on the other hand, if my books
aren't being read in 100 years,

132
00:19:46,728 --> 00:19:48,772
why bother to write?

133
00:19:50,523 --> 00:19:56,029
Tell me, Professor, why did you
get involved in this business?

134
00:19:56,112 --> 00:19:59,366
What's the Zone to you?

135
00:19:59,449 --> 00:20:02,911
Well, in a sense, I'm a scientist.

136
00:20:05,330 --> 00:20:07,082
What's in it for you?

137
00:20:08,708 --> 00:20:10,085
A fashionable author...

138
00:20:11,461 --> 00:20:14,255
...women draped all over you.

139
00:20:14,339 --> 00:20:17,550
I've lost my inspiration.

140
00:20:17,634 --> 00:20:19,344
I'm going to beg for some.

141
00:20:20,887 --> 00:20:23,223
So you've exhausted your talent?

142
00:20:23,306 --> 00:20:27,018
What? Yes, in a way.

143
00:20:29,354 --> 00:20:32,607
Do you hear that? That's our train.

144
00:20:40,115 --> 00:20:42,951
Did you take the top off the car?
- It's off.

145
00:20:56,047 --> 00:20:57,424
Rueger.

146
00:21:00,593 --> 00:21:03,012
If | don't come back, tell my wife.

147
00:21:18,528 --> 00:21:21,448
Damn! | forgot to buy cigarettes.

148
00:21:22,991 --> 00:21:24,742
Don't go back.

149
00:21:25,952 --> 00:21:28,788
- What is it?
- Well...

150
00:21:28,872 --> 00:21:32,250
- You're all like that.
- Like what?

151
00:21:32,333 --> 00:21:34,544
You believe any superstitious rubbish.

152
00:21:35,712 --> 00:21:38,047
l'll have to save these for a rainy day.

153
00:21:41,676 --> 00:21:43,386
Are you really a scientist?

154
00:23:21,025 --> 00:23:22,360
Get down!

155
00:23:26,155 --> 00:23:27,490
Keep still!

156
00:23:58,271 --> 00:23:59,939
See if anyone's there.

157
00:24:05,862 --> 00:24:07,989
Hurry, for God's sake!

158
00:24:13,786 --> 00:24:15,622
There's nobody here.

159
00:24:15,705 --> 00:24:17,457
Go to the other door.

160
00:24:44,651 --> 00:24:46,736
Get going, Writer.

161
00:26:58,451 --> 00:27:00,369
Keep your eyes open.

162
00:27:56,092 --> 00:27:58,511
Did you bring the gasoline can?

163
00:27:58,594 --> 00:28:00,638
Yes. A full one.

164
00:28:14,193 --> 00:28:16,612
What | said about going there...

165
00:28:17,864 --> 00:28:22,618
It's all a lie.
| don't give a damn about inspiration.

166
00:28:23,494 --> 00:28:27,164
But how can | put a name to...

167
00:28:28,624 --> 00:28:30,501
...what it is that | want?

168
00:28:30,585 --> 00:28:34,964
How am | to Know | don't want what | want

169
00:28:35,047 --> 00:28:39,427
or that | really don't want
what | don't want?

170
00:28:40,595 --> 00:28:43,514
These are intangibles where
the moment you name them,

171
00:28:43,598 --> 00:28:48,352
their meaning evaporates
like jellyfish in the sun.

172
00:28:48,436 --> 00:28:49,937
You've seen them around.

173
00:28:51,188 --> 00:28:54,817
My consciousness
wants the triumph of vegetarianism.

174
00:28:54,901 --> 00:28:58,154
My subconscious longs for a juicy steak.

175
00:28:59,322 --> 00:29:00,907
So what do | want?

176
00:29:02,366 --> 00:29:06,913
| want world supremacy, at the very least.

177
00:29:10,374 --> 00:29:12,835
Why do they need a train in the Zone?

178
00:29:12,919 --> 00:29:18,925
It won't go beyond the military post.
The guards won't venture in there.

179
00:29:27,183 --> 00:29:28,684
Everyone in their places?

180
00:30:42,425 --> 00:30:43,759
Hurry!

181
00:31:39,774 --> 00:31:45,237
Listen. Go and see
if there's a railcar there.

182
00:31:45,321 --> 00:31:47,698
- What railcar?
- Hurry up!

183
00:32:10,554 --> 00:32:12,264
Get back. I'll go.

184
00:34:09,131 --> 00:34:10,633
The gasoline can.

185
00:34:36,033 --> 00:34:37,326
Give it to me.

186
00:34:39,620 --> 00:34:42,331
Leave your rucksack. It's in the way.

187
00:34:42,414 --> 00:34:44,708
| see you're traveling light.

188
00:34:47,962 --> 00:34:52,341
If anyone's hit, don't cry out.
If they spot you, they'll kill you.

189
00:34:53,384 --> 00:34:57,388
Then when everything's quiet,
crawl back to the post.

190
00:34:57,471 --> 00:34:58,973
You'll be picked up later.

191
00:35:15,155 --> 00:35:16,865
Won't they come after us?

192
00:35:16,949 --> 00:35:20,452
No, they're scared to death of it.

193
00:35:21,578 --> 00:35:22,913
Of what?

194
00:39:43,048 --> 00:39:46,802
Here we are, home at last.

195
00:39:50,806 --> 00:39:52,307
It's so still.

196
00:39:54,977 --> 00:39:57,312
It's the quietest place on earth.

197
00:39:59,314 --> 00:40:01,316
You'll see for yourself.

198
00:40:03,151 --> 00:40:07,114
It's so beautiful. There's no one here.

199
00:40:07,197 --> 00:40:08,699
We're here.

200
00:40:08,782 --> 00:40:12,119
Three men can't foul it up in one day.

201
00:40:12,202 --> 00:40:14,288
Why can't we? Sure we can.

202
00:40:18,125 --> 00:40:21,920
Strange, the flowers have no scent.

203
00:40:22,004 --> 00:40:25,424
Don't you feel it?

204
00:40:25,507 --> 00:40:28,260
It stinks like a swamp.

205
00:40:28,343 --> 00:40:30,512
No, that's the river.

206
00:40:32,180 --> 00:40:38,145
There used to be flower beds here,
but Porcupine trampled on them.

207
00:40:38,895 --> 00:40:43,567
But their scent lingered on
for many years.

208
00:40:45,110 --> 00:40:48,614
Why did he wipe them out?

209
00:40:48,697 --> 00:40:50,198
| don't Know.

210
00:40:51,992 --> 00:40:53,744
| asked him why.

211
00:40:55,078 --> 00:40:57,080
He said, "One day, you'll understand."

212
00:40:59,166 --> 00:41:03,337
| think he simply began to hate the Zone.

213
00:41:07,382 --> 00:41:11,386
Is Porcupine his real name?

214
00:41:11,470 --> 00:41:14,222
No, a nickname. Like yours.

215
00:41:15,891 --> 00:41:19,394
For years he brought people into the Zone,
and nobody could stop him.

216
00:41:20,395 --> 00:41:21,730
He was my teacher.

217
00:41:23,231 --> 00:41:25,025
He opened my eyes.

218
00:41:27,653 --> 00:41:32,115
They didn't call him Porcupine then,
but Teacher.

219
00:41:34,451 --> 00:41:39,414
Then something happened to him.
Something broke inside him.

220
00:41:41,375 --> 00:41:43,835
| think he was being punished.

221
00:41:43,919 --> 00:41:48,090
Help me. Tie the bandage strips
to these metal nuts.

222
00:41:49,091 --> 00:41:53,011
ll just take a walk.

223
00:41:54,805 --> 00:41:56,139
| need...

224
00:42:09,778 --> 00:42:12,656
Be careful when you walk here.

225
00:42:18,787 --> 00:42:20,414
Where did he go?

226
00:42:21,707 --> 00:42:23,917
Perhaps he just wants to be alone.

227
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:28,755
Why? Even with three of us here,
| feel uneasy.

228
00:42:31,133 --> 00:42:33,969
He's back in the Zone.
Remember, he's a stalker.

229
00:42:35,637 --> 00:42:37,597
What of it?

230
00:42:38,557 --> 00:42:42,477
You see, stalking is a kind of vocation.

231
00:42:43,478 --> 00:42:47,149
- | imagined stalkers to be different.
- How so?

232
00:42:47,232 --> 00:42:52,028
Like Leatherstocking
or Chingachgook or Big Snake.

233
00:42:52,112 --> 00:42:55,574
Our stalker's biography
is more terrifying.

234
00:42:55,657 --> 00:42:59,244
He was in prison several times,
and he was crippled here.

235
00:42:59,327 --> 00:43:02,748
His daughter is a mutant,
a so-called Zone victim.

236
00:43:02,831 --> 00:43:04,624
They say she has no legs.

237
00:43:08,879 --> 00:43:11,548
What did he mean about the Porcupine?

238
00:43:12,466 --> 00:43:15,552
What did he mean he was punished?

239
00:43:16,011 --> 00:43:17,888
What is that, a figure of speech?

240
00:43:20,766 --> 00:43:23,477
One fine day,

241
00:43:23,560 --> 00:43:26,813
Porcupine returned from this place

242
00:43:26,897 --> 00:43:28,857
and suddenly became rich.

243
00:43:31,026 --> 00:43:32,611
Incredibly rich.

244
00:43:32,694 --> 00:43:34,654
You call that a punishment?

245
00:43:36,364 --> 00:43:39,159
Within a week, he had hanged himself.

246
00:43:39,576 --> 00:43:41,870
- Why?
- Quiet!

247
00:43:45,540 --> 00:43:47,375
What is it?

248
00:45:43,325 --> 00:45:48,246
About 20 years ago,
they say a meteorite fell here.

249
00:45:49,456 --> 00:45:51,416
It razed the settlement.

250
00:45:53,043 --> 00:45:57,172
They searched for it,
but they found nothing, of course.

251
00:45:59,341 --> 00:46:01,676
Why "of course"?

252
00:46:01,760 --> 00:46:03,970
Then people began to vanish.

253
00:46:05,388 --> 00:46:10,101
Finally, it was decided —
- Well?

254
00:46:10,185 --> 00:46:13,146
Finally, it was decided

255
00:46:13,229 --> 00:46:18,026
that this meteorite
was not quite a meteorite.

256
00:46:18,860 --> 00:46:20,362
So, for a start...

257
00:46:23,114 --> 00:46:28,370
...they put up barbed wire to stop
the inquisitive taking risks.

258
00:46:31,456 --> 00:46:36,503
Then rumors began that somewhere
in the Zone there's a place...

259
00:46:39,506 --> 00:46:41,675
...where desires come true.

260
00:46:42,342 --> 00:46:48,640
Well, naturally, they started
to guard the Zone like a treasure.

261
00:46:50,725 --> 00:46:54,604
For who knows what desires
a person might have?

262
00:46:55,397 --> 00:46:58,525
What was it if it wasn't a meteorite?

263
00:47:01,861 --> 00:47:03,446
Nobody knows.

264
00:47:05,240 --> 00:47:07,409
But what do you think it was?

265
00:47:09,369 --> 00:47:13,081
| don't have any idea.
It could have been anything.

266
00:47:15,458 --> 00:47:19,170
A message to mankind,
as a colleague of mine says.

267
00:47:19,671 --> 00:47:21,214
Or a gift.

268
00:47:26,261 --> 00:47:28,138
Some gift.

269
00:47:29,431 --> 00:47:31,599
Why would they want to do that?

270
00:47:31,683 --> 00:47:33,601
To make us happy.

271
00:47:38,106 --> 00:47:42,110
The flowers are blooming again,
but they've no scent.

272
00:47:43,319 --> 00:47:48,533
Forgive me for leaving you here,
but it was too early to go on.

273
00:47:52,078 --> 00:47:54,039
Did you hear that?

274
00:47:55,415 --> 00:47:59,878
- Maybe there are people living here.
- Who?

275
00:48:02,464 --> 00:48:04,883
You told me the story yourself.

276
00:48:04,966 --> 00:48:10,472
Those travelers who were here
when the Zone appeared.

277
00:48:10,555 --> 00:48:13,099
There's no one in the Zone.
There can't be.

278
00:48:18,021 --> 00:48:19,773
Are we ready to start?

279
00:49:06,903 --> 00:49:08,321
How do we get back?

280
00:49:09,405 --> 00:49:12,826
- Nobody finds their way back from here.
- What do you mean?

281
00:49:14,160 --> 00:49:16,663
We'll proceed as agreed.

282
00:49:22,252 --> 00:49:25,130
Each time, I'll point out the path.

283
00:49:25,213 --> 00:49:27,173
It's dangerous to veer from it.

284
00:49:29,759 --> 00:49:32,303
Keep the last pole in sight.

285
00:49:33,388 --> 00:49:36,724
You go first, Professor.

286
00:49:49,070 --> 00:49:50,572
Now you.

287
00:49:58,788 --> 00:50:01,166
Try to follow in his tracks.

288
00:51:20,119 --> 00:51:22,914
Lord! Where's —

289
00:51:23,581 --> 00:51:27,627
Did they remain here, the people?

290
00:51:28,294 --> 00:51:31,005
Nobody knows.

291
00:51:31,089 --> 00:51:36,427
| only recall them leaving
from our station to come here to the Zone.

292
00:51:37,136 --> 00:51:39,013
| was still a kid then.

293
00:51:39,597 --> 00:51:43,643
Everyone thought
someone wanted to conquer us.

294
00:51:50,692 --> 00:51:52,443
Go on, Professor.

295
00:52:01,035 --> 00:52:02,537
Now you, Writer.

296
00:54:32,770 --> 00:54:34,522
The Room is over there.

297
00:54:36,816 --> 00:54:38,317
We go this way.

298
00:54:38,860 --> 00:54:43,364
Are you trying to make it seem hard?
You can almost wrap your arms around it.

299
00:54:45,032 --> 00:54:48,202
Yes, but you need very long arms.

300
00:54:49,912 --> 00:54:51,414
We don't have it.

301
00:55:59,106 --> 00:56:00,691
Leave it!

302
00:56:02,443 --> 00:56:04,612
Don't — Don't touch it!

303
00:56:07,782 --> 00:56:09,951
| said don't touch it!

304
00:56:10,034 --> 00:56:14,539
What, are you crazy?
What was that for?

305
00:56:16,749 --> 00:56:19,126
| said this wasn't the place for a stroll.

306
00:56:20,670 --> 00:56:23,506
The Zone demands respect,
otherwise it'll punish you.

307
00:56:23,589 --> 00:56:27,260
Don't try anything like that again.

308
00:56:27,343 --> 00:56:29,303
Has the cat got your tongue?

309
00:56:30,972 --> 00:56:33,641
- | asked you not to.
- Do we go this way?

310
00:56:36,477 --> 00:56:40,982
Yes. To the left.
But we don't go in a direct line.

311
00:56:42,441 --> 00:56:44,569
We'll go roundabout.

312
00:56:45,903 --> 00:56:47,071
Why?

313
00:56:48,823 --> 00:56:52,910
Here, the straight path isn't shortest.

314
00:56:52,994 --> 00:56:55,454
The more indirect, the less risk there is.

315
00:56:55,538 --> 00:56:57,456
Is it fatal to go straight anead?

316
00:56:57,540 --> 00:57:00,918
- | told you. It's dangerous.
- Is the detour less dangerous?

317
00:57:01,002 --> 00:57:03,129
It's not, but nobody goes straight...

318
00:57:03,212 --> 00:57:04,922
You and your detours!

319
00:57:05,548 --> 00:57:08,259
How about if | just go straight?
- Listen. You —

320
00:57:08,342 --> 00:57:12,346
Why can't we go straight ahead?
It's right under our noses.

321
00:57:12,430 --> 00:57:15,850
It's risky here, risky there.
What the hell.

322
00:57:15,933 --> 00:57:19,186
You know your attitude about this
is very irresponsible.

323
00:57:21,272 --> 00:57:24,442
I'm fed up with your nuts and bandages.

324
00:57:24,525 --> 00:57:28,029
Forget it. I'm going this way.

325
00:57:28,446 --> 00:57:31,490
- The man's crazy.
- And | return the compliment.

326
00:57:32,116 --> 00:57:33,618
May |?

327
00:57:45,796 --> 00:57:47,465
The wind is rising.

328
00:57:49,258 --> 00:57:51,886
Do you feel it? The grass...

329
00:58:00,728 --> 00:58:04,065
Okay, all the more reason.

330
00:58:04,857 --> 00:58:06,359
What do you mean?

331
00:58:23,084 --> 00:58:25,461
- Hold it.
- Take your hands off me.

332
00:58:26,796 --> 00:58:27,963
All right.

333
00:58:29,090 --> 00:58:32,259
Then let the professor be my witness.

334
00:58:32,343 --> 00:58:35,930
I'm didn't send you in there.
You're going of your own free will.

335
00:58:36,013 --> 00:58:38,015
Of my own free will. What else?

336
00:58:39,266 --> 00:58:41,686
Nothing. Go on.

337
00:58:48,651 --> 00:58:50,903
And hope to God you're lucky.

338
00:59:05,793 --> 00:59:07,712
Listen!

339
00:59:07,795 --> 00:59:13,759
If you suddenly notice something
or feel something strange,

340
00:59:13,843 --> 00:59:16,762
turn right back.

341
00:59:16,846 --> 00:59:19,473
Just don't throw a lump of iron
at my head.

342
01:00:29,210 --> 01:00:30,711
Stop! Don't move!

343
01:00:35,758 --> 01:00:39,220
- Why did you do that?
- Do what?

344
01:00:39,303 --> 01:00:41,722
Why did you stop him?

345
01:00:42,556 --> 01:00:44,308
| thought you did.

346
01:01:24,306 --> 01:01:28,394
What happened? Why did you stop me?

347
01:01:29,144 --> 01:01:32,356
- | didn't stop you.
- Who did then?

348
01:01:32,439 --> 01:01:33,774
You?

349
01:01:37,444 --> 01:01:39,613
What the hell.

350
01:01:41,615 --> 01:01:44,159
You're a fine one, Mr. Shakespeare.

351
01:01:44,785 --> 01:01:47,788
Afraid to advance, ashamed to retreat.

352
01:01:47,872 --> 01:01:51,458
So you order yourself to stop
in a false voice.

353
01:01:51,542 --> 01:01:53,961
Fear's sobered you up.

354
01:01:54,044 --> 01:01:56,046
- What?
- Shut up.

355
01:01:56,130 --> 01:01:59,508
- Why'd you empty my bottle?
- | demand discipline!

356
01:02:15,524 --> 01:02:17,318
The Zone is...

357
01:02:18,444 --> 01:02:24,033
...a very complex maze of traps.

358
01:02:25,075 --> 01:02:26,827
All of them are death traps.

359
01:02:29,538 --> 01:02:32,917
| don't know what happens here
when humans aren't around.

360
01:02:33,000 --> 01:02:38,339
But as soon as humans appear,
everything begins to change.

361
01:02:41,050 --> 01:02:43,719
Former traps disappear, new ones appear.

362
01:02:45,638 --> 01:02:47,973
Safe ways become impassable.

363
01:02:49,850 --> 01:02:52,728
The way becomes now easy,

364
01:02:52,811 --> 01:02:54,647
now confused beyond words.

365
01:02:59,443 --> 01:03:00,945
This is the Zone.

366
01:03:02,529 --> 01:03:05,866
It might seem capricious.

367
01:03:07,451 --> 01:03:11,622
But at each moment, it's as if we construct it
according to our state of mind.

368
01:03:14,500 --> 01:03:20,089
| won't hide the fact that some people
turned back half-way.

369
01:03:21,423 --> 01:03:24,677
Some perished
on the threshold of the Room.

370
01:03:26,136 --> 01:03:29,348
But everything that happens here
depends on us.

371
01:03:29,723 --> 01:03:33,352
So the Zone lets the good through
and kills the evil?

372
01:03:34,645 --> 01:03:36,438
| don't Know. | don't believe that.

373
01:03:36,522 --> 01:03:41,986
| think it lets through
those who've lost all hope.

374
01:03:42,486 --> 01:03:46,824
Not the good or the bad, but the unhappy.

375
01:03:47,950 --> 01:03:52,246
But even the most unhappy will perish
if they don't know how to behave here.

376
01:04:02,089 --> 01:04:05,718
You're lucky. The Zone warned you.

377
01:04:10,180 --> 01:04:15,602
If you don't mind,
ll wait here till you come back.

378
01:04:17,438 --> 01:04:19,440
You'll return happy men.

379
01:04:19,815 --> 01:04:22,693
- That's impossible.
- Believe me.

380
01:04:22,776 --> 01:04:24,820
I've got sandwiches and a thermos.

381
01:04:24,903 --> 01:04:27,865
- First, you won't survive an hour.
- And second?

382
01:04:27,948 --> 01:04:30,701
What's more,
nobody returns the same way.

383
01:04:33,412 --> 01:04:35,497
All the same, I'd prefer it.

384
01:04:35,581 --> 01:04:38,208
Then we'll go back immediately.

385
01:04:38,667 --> 01:04:44,798
'll refund your money
minus a small sum for my trouble.

386
01:04:45,966 --> 01:04:47,843
Sobered up, Professor?

387
01:04:53,265 --> 01:04:56,185
All right. Toss the metal nut.

388
01:05:48,862 --> 01:05:52,533
Part Two

389
01:05:54,701 --> 01:06:00,707
STALKER

390
01:06:03,585 --> 01:06:06,505
Where are you? Come here!

391
01:06:11,927 --> 01:06:13,554
Are you tired?

392
01:06:29,278 --> 01:06:30,946
Oh, Lord.

393
01:06:34,533 --> 01:06:39,204
Judging by his tone of voice,
he'll lecture us again.

394
01:06:58,724 --> 01:07:01,101
May everything come true.

395
01:07:02,811 --> 01:07:04,855
May they believe.

396
01:07:06,773 --> 01:07:09,484
And may they laugh at their own passions.

397
01:07:10,360 --> 01:07:14,907
For what they call passion
is not really the energy of the soul,

398
01:07:14,990 --> 01:07:17,826
but merely friction between the soul
and the outside world.

399
01:07:19,661 --> 01:07:23,832
But, above all, may they believe
in themselves

400
01:07:23,916 --> 01:07:27,544
and become as helpless as children.

401
01:07:27,628 --> 01:07:31,465
For softness is great
and strength is worthless.

402
01:07:36,470 --> 01:07:39,389
When a man is born,
he ts soft and pliable.

403
01:07:40,307 --> 01:07:43,018
When he dies, he is strong and hard.

404
01:07:44,686 --> 01:07:47,731
When a tree grows, it is soft and pliable.

405
01:07:48,148 --> 01:07:52,319
But when it is dry and hard, it dies.

406
01:07:53,654 --> 01:07:57,824
Hardness and strength
are death's companions.

407
01:07:59,493 --> 01:08:03,288
Flexibility and softness
are the embodiment of life.

408
01:08:04,915 --> 01:08:09,253
That which has become hard
shall not triumph.

409
01:08:29,356 --> 01:08:30,691
Come here.

410
01:08:32,776 --> 01:08:34,778
It will fit very well.

411
01:08:34,861 --> 01:08:37,406
Soon we'll reach the dry tunnel.

412
01:08:37,489 --> 01:08:39,616
Careful. Don't jinx us.

413
01:08:39,700 --> 01:08:44,413
- Are we already on our way?
- Of course. Why?

414
01:08:44,496 --> 01:08:49,793
| thought you only wanted
to show us something.

415
01:08:49,876 --> 01:08:53,046
What about my rucksack?
- What happened to it?

416
01:08:53,130 --> 01:08:57,384
| left it back there.
| didn't know we were going.

417
01:08:57,884 --> 01:09:01,096
- It can't be helped.
- Why not?

418
01:09:01,179 --> 01:09:03,515
I've got to go back.
- It's not possible.

419
01:09:03,598 --> 01:09:06,518
- | can't go without my rucksack.
- There's no going back.

420
01:09:06,601 --> 01:09:09,730
Nobody goes back
the same way they came.

421
01:09:11,648 --> 01:09:15,319
Forget your rucksack.
What's in it? Diamonds?

422
01:09:15,402 --> 01:09:20,449
You'll lose your way.
The Room will give you all you desire.

423
01:09:20,532 --> 01:09:23,076
It will snow you under with rucksacks.

424
01:09:23,160 --> 01:09:25,662
Is it far to this Room?

425
01:09:25,746 --> 01:09:30,834
Straight ahead, 200 meters,
but there are no direct paths.

426
01:09:30,917 --> 01:09:32,252
Let's go.

427
01:09:33,628 --> 01:09:36,590
Don't let doubt creep in, Professor.

428
01:09:37,341 --> 01:09:39,384
Miracles are outside your experience.

429
01:09:41,386 --> 01:09:44,306
Remember how St. Peter nearly drowned.

430
01:09:48,935 --> 01:09:50,437
Go, Writer.

431
01:09:52,647 --> 01:09:55,942
- Go where?
- Down the ladder.

432
01:10:06,953 --> 01:10:09,122
Professor, where are you?

433
01:12:00,442 --> 01:12:04,404
- This is the dry tunnel.
- You Call this dry?

434
01:12:06,323 --> 01:12:11,328
It's a local joke.
Usually we have to swim it.

435
01:12:40,273 --> 01:12:42,526
Wait. Where's the professor?

436
01:12:42,609 --> 01:12:45,946
- What?
- The professor's lost.

437
01:12:46,029 --> 01:12:47,906
Professor! Professor!

438
01:12:47,989 --> 01:12:50,617
He was following you the entire time.

439
01:12:51,409 --> 01:12:54,538
He must have strayed and lost his way.

440
01:12:54,621 --> 01:12:58,416
He didn't lose his way.
He went back for his rucksack.

441
01:12:59,125 --> 01:13:00,835
Now he'll never get out.

442
01:13:02,295 --> 01:13:07,342
- Shall we wait for him?
- We can't. Things change every minute.

443
01:13:07,425 --> 01:13:09,386
The two of us must go on.

444
01:13:38,540 --> 01:13:41,293
Look! What"s all this?

445
01:13:41,376 --> 01:13:44,921
- | told you about it.
- About what?

446
01:13:45,005 --> 01:13:47,507
This is the Zone. Do you understand?

447
01:13:47,591 --> 01:13:50,719
We have to hurry. Let's go.

448
01:14:11,698 --> 01:14:13,199
Here he is.

449
01:14:26,588 --> 01:14:30,508
| really appreciate that you...

450
01:14:30,592 --> 01:14:32,344
How did you get here?

451
01:14:34,596 --> 01:14:40,602
Most of the way, | crawled on all fours.

452
01:14:41,936 --> 01:14:44,397
Incredible.
How did you manage to overtake us?

453
01:14:46,066 --> 01:14:47,942
Overtake you?

454
01:14:49,235 --> 01:14:53,156
| came back here for my rucksack.

455
01:14:53,239 --> 01:14:56,117
Where did the metal nut come from?

456
01:14:58,912 --> 01:15:00,372
My God.

457
01:15:01,039 --> 01:15:03,708
It's a trap.

458
01:15:07,754 --> 01:15:11,633
Porcupine hung it here on purpose.

459
01:15:15,136 --> 01:15:19,766
How did the Zone let us through?

460
01:15:25,647 --> 01:15:27,107
Lord.

461
01:15:28,316 --> 01:15:30,777
| won't take another step until —

462
01:15:31,945 --> 01:15:33,738
A good deal.

463
01:15:38,952 --> 01:15:40,286
Enough.

464
01:15:41,955 --> 01:15:43,248
So.

465
01:15:55,760 --> 01:15:57,846
We'll all rest here.

466
01:15:57,929 --> 01:16:01,141
But keep away
from that metal nut in any case.

467
01:16:01,224 --> 01:16:05,395
| didn't think Professor would get out.

468
01:16:08,857 --> 01:16:13,069
| never know what sort of people
I'm bringing in.

469
01:16:13,153 --> 01:16:17,532
It's only in here that things
become clear, when it's too late.

470
01:16:18,658 --> 01:16:23,955
The main thing is that the professor's
rucksack and spare pants are safe.

471
01:16:25,248 --> 01:16:28,585
Don't poke your nose
into another guy's drawers,

472
01:16:28,668 --> 01:16:30,378
if you know what | mean.

473
01:16:30,462 --> 01:16:32,839
What's there to understand?

474
01:16:33,757 --> 01:16:39,763
Don't pull my leg with your binomial theorem
and your psychological explanations.

475
01:16:40,138 --> 01:16:42,932
We're out of favor at the institute.

476
01:16:43,016 --> 01:16:45,310
We're refused funds for an expedition.

477
01:16:46,561 --> 01:16:51,107
So let's fill the rucksack
with manometers, shit-ometers...

478
01:16:52,692 --> 01:16:54,986
...Slip into the Zone illegally...

479
01:16:56,529 --> 01:16:58,990
...and check all the local miracles
with algebra.

480
01:17:01,743 --> 01:17:05,079
No one in the world
has any conception about the Zone,

481
01:17:05,163 --> 01:17:07,457
so it'll be a sensation.

482
01:17:07,540 --> 01:17:12,003
Television,
your lady fans getting hot flashes,

483
01:17:12,086 --> 01:17:14,380
people carrying brooms
as if they were laurel wreaths.

484
01:17:15,131 --> 01:17:21,471
Then our professor appears all in white
and declaims,

485
01:17:22,055 --> 01:17:25,642
"Mene, mene. Tekel upharsin."

486
01:17:25,725 --> 01:17:32,649
Naturally, everyone gapes and shouts,
"Give him the Nobel Prize!"

487
01:17:35,568 --> 01:17:41,991
You bedraggled hack writer.
You homegrown psychologist.

488
01:17:42,075 --> 01:17:47,872
Fit only to scribble graffiti
in lavatories, you talentless clod.

489
01:17:49,040 --> 01:17:53,211
That's feeble stuff. Call that an insult?

490
01:17:54,420 --> 01:17:57,590
You don't know how it's done.

491
01:17:57,674 --> 01:18:01,511
All right.
Suppose |'m after a Nobel Prize.

492
01:18:01,594 --> 01:18:04,764
What are you after?

493
01:18:04,848 --> 01:18:09,686
Want to bestow on mankind
the pearls of your bought inspiration?

494
01:18:11,104 --> 01:18:13,189
| spit on mankind.

495
01:18:14,148 --> 01:18:19,112
In all of your mankind,
only one man interests me.

496
01:18:19,195 --> 01:18:21,030
And that's me.

497
01:18:21,114 --> 01:18:26,870
Am | worth anything,
or am | shit like certain other people?

498
01:18:26,953 --> 01:18:30,540
What if you find out
that's indeed what you are?

499
01:18:30,623 --> 01:18:35,879
Know something, Einstein?
| don't want to argue with you.

500
01:18:38,965 --> 01:18:42,969
Truth is born in arguments, damn it.

501
01:18:46,055 --> 01:18:49,100
Listen, Chingachgook.

502
01:18:52,353 --> 01:18:56,232
You've brought so many people here.

503
01:18:58,318 --> 01:19:00,987
Not as many as | would like.

504
01:19:01,070 --> 01:19:03,907
It doesn't matter.

505
01:19:03,990 --> 01:19:07,452
Why did they come? What were they after?

506
01:19:07,535 --> 01:19:09,203
Happiness, more than anything.

507
01:19:09,287 --> 01:19:13,166
Yes, but what kind of happiness?

508
01:19:16,002 --> 01:19:20,381
People don't like to reveal
their innermost thoughts.

509
01:19:20,465 --> 01:19:24,344
Anyway, that concerns neither you nor me.

510
01:19:24,427 --> 01:19:27,138
You've been lucky.

511
01:19:27,221 --> 01:19:31,601
All my life, | have never seen
one happy person.

512
01:19:31,684 --> 01:19:33,978
Nor have lI.

513
01:19:34,062 --> 01:19:37,482
They return from the Room,
and | guide them back.

514
01:19:37,565 --> 01:19:39,776
And we never meet again.

515
01:19:42,195 --> 01:19:44,864
Wishes don't come true immediately,
you know.

516
01:19:46,366 --> 01:19:52,288
And you've never wanted
to make use of this Room?

517
01:19:57,210 --> 01:19:59,462
I'm fine as | am.

518
01:20:51,723 --> 01:20:54,267
Professor, listen.

519
01:20:56,519 --> 01:20:59,439
I'm thinking about inspiration you can buy.

520
01:21:02,150 --> 01:21:09,157
Suppose | return to our godforsaken city
a genius. Understand?

521
01:21:16,330 --> 01:21:20,960
But a man writes because he's tormented,
unsure of himself.

522
01:21:23,296 --> 01:21:28,885
He has to keep proving his worth
to himself and to others.

523
01:21:31,929 --> 01:21:34,974
But if I'm convinced I'm a genius...

524
01:21:37,435 --> 01:21:39,562
...then why do | need to write?

525
01:21:41,898 --> 01:21:43,649
What's the deal?

526
01:21:46,444 --> 01:21:52,492
Anyway, | must say we exist in order to —

527
01:21:52,575 --> 01:21:55,828
Just leave me in peace.

528
01:21:58,122 --> 01:22:02,293
Let me nap a little.
| didn't sleep all last night.

529
01:22:03,336 --> 01:22:06,464
Keep your complexes to yourself.

530
01:22:06,547 --> 01:22:11,552
At any rate, all your technology —

531
01:22:15,223 --> 01:22:17,642
all those blast furnaces, wheels...

532
01:22:19,727 --> 01:22:23,773
...and suchlike hustle and bustle

533
01:22:23,856 --> 01:22:27,527
so that people can work less
and consume more...

534
01:22:29,403 --> 01:22:32,365
...they're all crutches, artificial limbs.

535
01:22:35,201 --> 01:22:38,746
Mankind exists in order to —

536
01:22:41,457 --> 01:22:43,793
to create works of art.

537
01:22:45,461 --> 01:22:50,883
At least that's unselfish
compared with all other human activities.

538
01:22:53,177 --> 01:22:58,391
Great illusions. Images of absolute truth.

539
01:23:00,268 --> 01:23:02,895
Are you listening to me, Professor?

540
01:23:04,480 --> 01:23:07,608
What unselfishness are you talking about?

541
01:23:07,692 --> 01:23:11,696
People keep dying of hunger.
Have you been living on the moon?

542
01:23:21,330 --> 01:23:25,001
And this is our intellectual aristocracy.

543
01:23:26,711 --> 01:23:29,714
You're unable to think in abstract terms.

544
01:23:31,507 --> 01:23:37,180
Why don't you teach me
the meaning of life...

545
01:23:40,600 --> 01:23:42,768
...and, at the same time, how to think.

546
01:23:43,603 --> 01:23:45,188
It's useless.

547
01:23:47,231 --> 01:23:49,901
You may be a professor,
but you're ignorant.

548
01:24:39,825 --> 01:24:44,163
'And, lo, there was a great earthquake,

549
01:24:45,665 --> 01:24:49,001
And the sun became black
as sackcloth of hair...

550
01:24:50,002 --> 01:24:53,089
...and the moon became as blood,

551
01:24:54,298 --> 01:24:58,135
And the stars of heaven
fell unto the earth,

552
01:24:58,219 --> 01:25:02,431
even as a fig tree casts its unripe figs

553
01:25:02,515 --> 01:25:06,310
when it is shaken by a mighty wind.

554
01:25:06,978 --> 01:25:11,107
And the heavens departed as a scroll;

555
01:25:11,190 --> 01:25:18,030
and every mountain and island
was moved out of its place.

556
01:25:21,909 --> 01:25:27,415
And the kings of the earth
and the great men

557
01:25:27,498 --> 01:25:33,212
and the rich men and the generals
and the mighty men...

558
01:25:34,630 --> 01:25:39,802
...and all free men
hid themselves in the dens

559
01:25:39,885 --> 01:25:41,846
and in the rocks of the mountains,

560
01:25:41,929 --> 01:25:44,265
And they said to the mountains and rocks,

561
01:25:44,348 --> 01:25:50,688
Fall on us and hide us from
the face of him that sits on the throne,

562
01:25:50,771 --> 01:25:53,649
and trom the wrath of the Lamb.

563
01:25:53,733 --> 01:25:57,987
For the great day of his wrath has come,

564
01:25:58,070 --> 01:26:02,033
and who shall be able to stand?"

565
01:29:03,422 --> 01:29:05,591
"That same day...

566
01:29:07,218 --> 01:29:09,887
...two of them...

567
01:29:10,763 --> 01:29:17,770
...were going to a village called Emmaus.

568
01:29:18,521 --> 01:29:22,358
And it came to pass

569
01:29:22,441 --> 01:29:29,949
that Jesus himself drew near
and walked with them,

570
01:29:30,449 --> 01:29:34,453
but they did not recognize him.

571
01:29:36,038 --> 01:29:38,249
'What manner of discussions are these...

572
01:29:40,876 --> 01:29:45,130
...that you have one to another
as you walk and are sad?'

573
01:29:45,214 --> 01:29:46,966
And one of them, named" —

574
01:30:01,313 --> 01:30:02,815
You awake?

575
01:30:08,988 --> 01:30:14,868
You were talking about
the meaning of our life...

576
01:30:16,328 --> 01:30:18,289
...the unselfishness of art.

577
01:30:22,209 --> 01:30:24,003
Now, take music.

578
01:30:30,384 --> 01:30:34,096
It's connected least of all with reality.

579
01:30:34,179 --> 01:30:38,100
Or, if connected, then it's without ideas.

580
01:30:38,183 --> 01:30:42,146
It's merely empty sound
without associations.

581
01:30:47,192 --> 01:30:52,615
Nevertheless, music miraculously
penetrates your very soul.

582
01:30:56,327 --> 01:31:00,205
What chord in us
responds to its harmonies...

583
01:31:01,332 --> 01:31:05,294
...transforming it
into a source of delight,

584
01:31:05,377 --> 01:31:08,672
uniting us and shattering us?

585
01:31:10,090 --> 01:31:14,219
Why is all this necessary?
And, above all, for whom?

586
01:31:17,431 --> 01:31:22,853
You'll reply, "For no one and no reason."

587
01:31:24,605 --> 01:31:28,484
No. | doubt that.

588
01:31:31,403 --> 01:31:34,573
For everything in the final reckoning
has a meaning.

589
01:31:36,492 --> 01:31:40,287
A meaning and a reason.

590
01:32:09,274 --> 01:32:12,778
You mean we go there?

591
01:32:15,531 --> 01:32:19,493
Unfortunately, there's no other way.

592
01:32:34,883 --> 01:32:39,221
It's rather gloomy, eh, Professor?

593
01:32:43,350 --> 01:32:46,145
| don't think | should go first here.

594
01:32:47,354 --> 01:32:50,065
Big Snake never volunteers.

595
01:32:51,900 --> 01:32:56,488
Obviously, we'll have to draw lots.

596
01:32:57,322 --> 01:33:00,075
Here, I'd prefer some volunteer.

597
01:33:03,287 --> 01:33:04,872
Got any matches?

598
01:33:13,213 --> 01:33:14,381
Thanks.

599
01:33:26,852 --> 01:33:28,687
The long match goes first.

600
01:33:31,857 --> 01:33:33,400
The long one.

601
01:33:40,365 --> 01:33:43,786
This time, you were out of luck.

602
01:33:59,176 --> 01:34:02,262
How about throwing a metal nut?

603
01:34:02,346 --> 01:34:04,681
Of course. You're welcome to.

604
01:34:42,094 --> 01:34:43,595
Another one?

605
01:34:52,563 --> 01:34:53,897
All right.

606
01:34:55,482 --> 01:34:56,817
I'm going.

607
01:36:43,715 --> 01:36:45,342
Hurry, Professor.

608
01:40:55,884 --> 01:40:57,469
Over here.

609
01:41:00,639 --> 01:41:03,058
There's some sort of door over here.

610
01:41:20,242 --> 01:41:21,785
Now it's over there.

611
01:41:22,994 --> 01:41:24,955
Open the door and go in.

612
01:41:33,380 --> 01:41:37,300
Me again? | should go in there?

613
01:41:37,384 --> 01:41:39,094
You drew your lot.

614
01:41:41,179 --> 01:41:43,014
You mustn't hang about.

615
01:41:47,686 --> 01:41:49,688
What have you got there?

616
01:41:49,771 --> 01:41:51,773
You can't go in there with a gun!

617
01:41:52,607 --> 01:41:55,443
You'll be killed, and you'll doom us!

618
01:41:55,527 --> 01:41:57,279
Remember the tanks!

619
01:41:58,196 --> 01:41:59,948
Put it away, | beg you.

620
01:42:00,031 --> 01:42:01,908
Don't you understand?

621
01:42:03,660 --> 01:42:06,746
If anything happens, | can get you out.

622
01:42:06,830 --> 01:42:08,331
But like this —

623
01:42:09,332 --> 01:42:11,876
Please, | beg you. And who —

624
01:42:13,878 --> 01:42:16,464
Who will you shoot at in there?

625
01:42:29,519 --> 01:42:31,938
Go! We've very little time.

626
01:42:35,942 --> 01:42:37,444
There's water here.

627
01:42:38,778 --> 01:42:41,364
Never mind. Hold onto the rail.

628
01:43:27,786 --> 01:43:31,831
Don't go any farther.
Wait for us up there by the exit.

629
01:43:46,346 --> 01:43:48,473
| hope you've nothing like that.

630
01:43:49,599 --> 01:43:52,310
- Like what?
- Like a pistol.

631
01:43:52,685 --> 01:43:55,230
I've an ampoule, for an emergency.

632
01:43:56,481 --> 01:44:00,944
- What kind of ampoule?
- For protection. Poison.

633
01:44:01,027 --> 01:44:04,280
Good God, you mean you came here to die?

634
01:44:10,495 --> 01:44:13,039
That's how it is, just in case.

635
01:44:40,650 --> 01:44:42,444
Back!

636
01:44:42,861 --> 01:44:45,155
Return, it's suicide!

637
01:44:45,238 --> 01:44:47,240
| told you to wait at the exit.

638
01:44:48,616 --> 01:44:50,034
Don't move!

639
01:45:36,581 --> 01:45:38,166
It's all because of your pipe.

640
01:45:38,249 --> 01:45:40,210
- What?
- Never mind.

641
01:45:40,793 --> 01:45:43,546
You should have gone first.

642
01:45:43,630 --> 01:45:46,591
He took the wrong turn out of fright.

643
01:47:32,864 --> 01:47:36,159
Another experiment.

644
01:47:38,536 --> 01:47:44,250
Experiments, facts or truth
as a last resort.

645
01:47:45,793 --> 01:47:49,213
But there's no such things as facts,
especially here.

646
01:47:50,757 --> 01:47:55,303
All this is someone's idiotic invention.

647
01:47:55,386 --> 01:47:57,639
Can't you tell?

648
01:48:00,183 --> 01:48:03,061
You, of course,
want to know whose invention.

649
01:48:05,772 --> 01:48:10,568
What good will it do you to know?

650
01:48:11,110 --> 01:48:15,448
Whose conscience will be bothered by it?
Mine?

651
01:48:16,574 --> 01:48:20,203
| have no conscience, only nerves.

652
01:48:20,870 --> 01:48:24,499
Some bastard abuses you, you're hurt.

653
01:48:24,582 --> 01:48:28,169
A different bastard praises you, you're hurt.

654
01:48:28,252 --> 01:48:33,174
You put your heart and soul
into your work, and they devour you.

655
01:48:35,385 --> 01:48:38,429
They even devour the filth in your soul.

656
01:48:39,681 --> 01:48:41,933
They're all literate.

657
01:48:44,060 --> 01:48:46,938
They all have voracious appetites.

658
01:48:47,980 --> 01:48:55,321
They all keep crowding round —
journalists, editors, critics,

659
01:48:55,405 --> 01:48:57,657
a constant stream of women.

660
01:48:58,574 --> 01:49:01,619
All of them clamoring for more.

661
01:49:04,997 --> 01:49:07,291
What kind of writer am I...

662
01:49:08,543 --> 01:49:10,712
... if | detest writing?

663
01:49:12,672 --> 01:49:16,718
If it's torture for me,
a painful, shameful occupation,

664
01:49:16,801 --> 01:49:19,220
something akin to extruding hemorrhoids.

665
01:49:22,807 --> 01:49:26,811
| used to think my books
helped some people to become better,

666
01:49:26,894 --> 01:49:28,896
but nobody needs me.

667
01:49:29,480 --> 01:49:33,693
If | die, in a couple days,
they'll find someone else to devour.

668
01:49:37,488 --> 01:49:39,532
| wanted to change them,

669
01:49:39,615 --> 01:49:44,537
but they've changed me
to fit their own image.

670
01:49:49,584 --> 01:49:54,380
Once, the future was only
a continuation of the present.

671
01:49:54,464 --> 01:49:58,134
All its changes loomed somewhere
beyond the horizon.

672
01:49:59,177 --> 01:50:01,846
But now the future's
a part of the present.

673
01:50:09,687 --> 01:50:11,773
Are they prepared for this?

674
01:50:12,732 --> 01:50:16,986
They don't want to know anything.
All they do is gobble.

675
01:50:31,709 --> 01:50:33,377
You certainly are lucky.

676
01:50:34,378 --> 01:50:39,383
Now you'll live to be a hundred.

677
01:50:53,231 --> 01:50:57,318
Why not forever?

678
01:51:00,404 --> 01:51:02,240
Like the Wandering Jew.

679
01:51:42,780 --> 01:51:46,534
You must surely be a fine person.

680
01:51:46,617 --> 01:51:49,120
Not that | doubted it.

681
01:51:49,203 --> 01:51:52,999
You must have been through such agony.

682
01:51:54,542 --> 01:51:57,545
This pipe is the most terrible part
of the Zone.

683
01:51:57,628 --> 01:52:03,050
They call it the meat grinder.
How many people has it ground up?

684
01:52:08,347 --> 01:52:11,601
Porcupine sent his brother through
instead of himself.

685
01:52:15,187 --> 01:52:17,565
He was so sensitive, so gifted.

686
01:52:19,984 --> 01:52:21,569
Listen to this.

687
01:52:23,487 --> 01:52:27,533
Now the summer is passed,
it might never have been;

688
01:52:28,659 --> 01:52:33,080
It is warm in the sun,
but it isn't enough;

689
01:52:33,706 --> 01:52:39,545
All that | could attain,
like a five-fingered leaf,

690
01:52:39,629 --> 01:52:44,383
fell straight into my hand,
but it isn't enough;

691
01:52:45,176 --> 01:52:50,556
Neither evil nor good
has yet vanished in vain;

692
01:52:50,640 --> 01:52:55,102
It all burned and was light,
but it isn't enough;

693
01:52:55,853 --> 01:53:00,524
Life has been like a shield
and has offered protection;

694
01:53:01,359 --> 01:53:05,696
| have been very lucky,
but it isn't enough;

695
01:53:06,530 --> 01:53:11,953
The leaves were not burned,
the boughs were not broken;

696
01:53:12,036 --> 01:53:17,124
The day shines like glass,
but it isn't enough.

697
01:53:19,210 --> 01:53:22,088
Fine, isn't it? That's his poem.

698
01:53:22,171 --> 01:53:26,300
Why are you evading things? "Fine" indeed!

699
01:53:26,384 --> 01:53:28,469
It makes me sick to look at you.

700
01:53:28,552 --> 01:53:32,431
You can't imagine how glad | am
that we made it.

701
01:53:32,515 --> 01:53:34,976
Your conduct was exemplary.

702
01:53:36,060 --> 01:53:39,563
You're fine, honest men.
I'm proud | was right.

703
01:53:39,647 --> 01:53:42,817
So he's happy we got back.
So happy he could choke.

704
01:53:43,859 --> 01:53:47,571
Fate! Zone! So I'm a fine fellow.

705
01:53:48,155 --> 01:53:51,617
Do you think | didn't see you
offer me two long matches?

706
01:53:51,701 --> 01:53:53,911
- You don't understand.
- No, of course not.

707
01:53:53,995 --> 01:54:00,334
I'm sorry, Professor, but this louse
chose you as his favorite.

708
01:54:00,418 --> 01:54:02,086
What are you going on about?

709
01:54:02,169 --> 01:54:05,881
He shoved me into the pipe
because I'm a second-rate person.

710
01:54:06,674 --> 01:54:09,135
Meat grinder! What a word!

711
01:54:10,177 --> 01:54:15,016
What right have you to choose who lives,
who goes into the meat grinder?

712
01:54:15,099 --> 01:54:17,351
You made the choice.

713
01:54:17,435 --> 01:54:22,231
What choice did | have —
one of two long matchsticks?

714
01:54:22,314 --> 01:54:24,567
Forget the matches.

715
01:54:24,650 --> 01:54:28,487
Back by the metal nut,
the Zone let you through

716
01:54:28,571 --> 01:54:31,782
to pass through the meat grinder.

717
01:54:32,283 --> 01:54:34,493
Is that for you?
- Who knows?

718
01:54:35,619 --> 01:54:40,416
| never choose. You can't imagine how
terrible it is to make the wrong choice.

719
01:54:41,500 --> 01:54:43,961
But someone has to go first.

720
01:54:44,045 --> 01:54:47,465
Yes? No, this isn't the clinic.

721
01:54:49,258 --> 01:54:52,887
Someone has to go first!
How would you like it?

722
01:54:59,977 --> 01:55:01,562
Don't touch it!

723
01:55:22,166 --> 01:55:25,044
- Yes?
- Laboratory Nine, please.

724
01:55:26,587 --> 01:55:28,172
One minute.

725
01:55:34,470 --> 01:55:35,596
/m listening.

726
01:55:35,679 --> 01:55:38,891
- | hope | haven't disturbed you.
- What do you want?

727
01:55:40,351 --> 01:55:42,186
Just a few words.

728
01:55:42,269 --> 01:55:47,149
You hid it. | found it
in the old building, Bunker 4.

729
01:55:49,610 --> 01:55:53,197
Are you listening?
-// inform the security service.

730
01:55:53,280 --> 01:55:58,869
Go on! Inform on me, write a denunciation.

731
01:55:58,953 --> 01:56:03,332
Set my colleagues against me.
But you're late.

732
01:56:03,415 --> 01:56:06,252
I'm just two steps away
from the place itself.

733
01:56:07,962 --> 01:56:09,797
Are you listening to me?

734
01:56:09,880 --> 01:56:12,466
You realize
this finishes you as a scientist?

735
01:56:12,550 --> 01:56:13,801
So be happy.

736
01:56:13,884 --> 01:56:16,887
Do you realize what happens if you dare?

737
01:56:19,348 --> 01:56:21,058
Trying to scare me again?

738
01:56:23,227 --> 01:56:29,150
Yes, all my life I've been scared.
Even of you.

739
01:56:29,233 --> 01:56:32,820
You don't scare me anymore.

740
01:56:32,903 --> 01:56:36,323
My God, youre not even Herostratus.

741
01:56:36,407 --> 01:56:43,289
You just wanted to trip me up because,
20 years ago, | slept with your wife.

742
01:56:43,372 --> 01:56:47,668
You've finally managed
to settle the score.

743
01:56:47,751 --> 01:56:52,089
Go on, do your dirty work.

744
01:56:53,215 --> 01:56:54,925
Don't dare hang up on me.

745
01:56:56,719 --> 01:56:59,763
Prison isnt the worst thing
that awaits you.

746
01:57:00,055 --> 01:57:03,184
You'll never forgive yourself for this.

747
01:57:03,267 --> 01:57:07,897
/ can see you hanging from your belt
over a prison /atrine.

748
01:57:10,900 --> 01:57:14,361
What are you up to, Professor?

749
01:57:15,905 --> 01:57:20,618
Imagine what will happen
when everyone believes in this Room...

750
01:57:22,119 --> 01:57:25,206
... and when they all come hurrying here.

751
01:57:26,207 --> 01:57:31,795
It's only a question of time.
Not today, but tomorrow.

752
01:57:31,879 --> 01:57:33,881
And in the thousands.

753
01:57:33,964 --> 01:57:37,218
All these would-be emperors,
grand inquisitors,

754
01:57:37,301 --> 01:57:39,053
fuhrers of all shades.

755
01:57:39,136 --> 01:57:43,307
The so-called saviors of mankind!

756
01:57:43,390 --> 01:57:47,978
And not for money or inspiration,
but to remake the world.

757
01:57:48,062 --> 01:57:52,775
- I'll never bring that sort here.
- What do you understand?

758
01:57:54,151 --> 01:57:56,820
You're not the only stalker in the world.

759
01:57:56,904 --> 01:58:02,701
No stalker Knows what ideas the people
you bring here take away with them.

760
01:58:03,410 --> 01:58:06,330
The number of motiveless crimes
is growing.

761
01:58:06,413 --> 01:58:08,249
Isn't that your work?

762
01:58:08,332 --> 01:58:10,000
What about the military coups?

763
01:58:11,460 --> 01:58:15,130
The mafia in the governments,
couldn't they be your clients?

764
01:58:15,756 --> 01:58:17,591
What about the lasers,

765
01:58:17,675 --> 01:58:24,473
the deadly bacteria hidden away
in vaults for the time being?

766
01:58:24,556 --> 01:58:27,768
Stop this sociological drivel!

767
01:58:27,851 --> 01:58:29,937
Do you really believe
in these fairy tales?

768
01:58:30,020 --> 01:58:34,775
Not in the good ones,
but in the terrifying ones, yes.

769
01:58:34,858 --> 01:58:36,944
Just stop it.

770
01:58:37,027 --> 01:58:43,075
No single individual can have
enough hatred or love

771
01:58:43,158 --> 01:58:45,953
to spread over all mankind.

772
01:58:47,121 --> 01:58:52,960
You desire money, a woman.
Or you want your boss to get run over.

773
01:58:53,043 --> 01:58:55,296
That's neither here nor there.

774
01:58:55,379 --> 01:58:58,424
But world domination, a just society,

775
01:58:58,507 --> 01:59:00,676
the kingdom of heaven on earth.

776
01:59:00,759 --> 01:59:05,639
Those aren't desires,
but an ideology, actions, concepts.

777
01:59:07,141 --> 01:59:12,438
Subconscious compassion
cannot yet be realized

778
01:59:12,521 --> 01:59:15,232
as a common instinctive desire.

779
01:59:16,025 --> 01:59:20,112
You can't be happy at the expense
of others' unhappiness.

780
01:59:21,155 --> 01:59:27,953
| see you've decided to smash humanity
with some inconceivable boon.

781
01:59:29,371 --> 01:59:31,874
Yet I'm completely calm.

782
01:59:31,957 --> 01:59:35,961
I'm not worried about you or myself
or mankind.

783
01:59:37,421 --> 01:59:39,923
Nothing will come of it.

784
01:59:40,966 --> 01:59:44,887
At best,
you'll receive your Nobel Prize...

785
01:59:46,347 --> 01:59:51,518
...or more probably something
quite inconceivable

786
01:59:51,602 --> 01:59:54,104
which you haven't even thought about.

787
01:59:54,438 --> 01:59:56,231
A telephone.

788
01:59:57,733 --> 02:00:02,112
You dream of one thing
and get something quite different.

789
02:00:04,073 --> 02:00:05,783
Why did you do that?

790
02:00:20,089 --> 02:00:23,592
A telephone, electricity.

791
02:00:27,638 --> 02:00:30,474
Look, sleeping pills.

792
02:00:31,266 --> 02:00:34,686
This sort isn't prescribed anymore.
Where did they come from?

793
02:00:39,441 --> 02:00:41,443
Shall we go there?

794
02:00:42,277 --> 02:00:46,740
It'll soon be evening,
too dark to get back.

795
02:00:53,872 --> 02:00:56,500
By the way,

796
02:00:56,583 --> 02:01:01,296
| can see that all this poetry reciting
and walking around

797
02:01:01,380 --> 02:01:05,175
is a new, original way of apologizing.

798
02:01:05,259 --> 02:01:06,760
| understand you.

799
02:01:08,887 --> 02:01:12,474
A difficult childhood environment.

800
02:01:12,558 --> 02:01:14,685
But don't fool yourself.

801
02:01:17,312 --> 02:01:19,064
| don't forgive you.

802
02:01:19,898 --> 02:01:22,067
Don't. Please.

803
02:02:14,786 --> 02:02:17,956
Professor, come here.

804
02:02:51,615 --> 02:02:55,369
Just a moment. No need to rush.

805
02:02:55,452 --> 02:02:57,621
I'm not rushing anywhere.

806
02:03:48,338 --> 02:03:50,173
Don't get angry.

807
02:03:53,510 --> 02:03:55,554
But | have to tell you.

808
02:04:02,603 --> 02:04:07,399
We're now standing at the threshold.

809
02:04:15,282 --> 02:04:20,203
This is the most important moment...
in your life.

810
02:04:23,540 --> 02:04:25,876
You must know that...

811
02:04:27,210 --> 02:04:32,049
... your most cherished desire
will come true here.

812
02:04:33,925 --> 02:04:39,556
Your sincerest wish, the desire
that has made you suffer most.

813
02:05:08,960 --> 02:05:10,587
There's no need to speak.

814
02:05:14,341 --> 02:05:20,097
You must only... concentrate

815
02:05:20,180 --> 02:05:23,266
and recall all your past life.

816
02:05:26,353 --> 02:05:31,608
When a man thinks of the past,
he becomes kinder.

817
02:05:32,693 --> 02:05:34,194
But the main thing —

818
02:06:08,103 --> 02:06:09,604
The main thing is...

819
02:06:14,359 --> 02:06:15,861
... you must believe.

820
02:06:25,328 --> 02:06:26,955
Now go.

821
02:06:32,836 --> 02:06:34,588
Who wants to go first?

822
02:06:39,676 --> 02:06:41,344
Perhaps you?

823
02:06:43,013 --> 02:06:46,057
Me? No, | don't want to.

824
02:06:47,184 --> 02:06:49,144
| Know it's not easy.

825
02:06:49,227 --> 02:06:52,230
But don't worry. That will soon pass.

826
02:06:53,523 --> 02:06:57,944
I'm not sure... that it will.

827
02:07:00,071 --> 02:07:03,575
Firstly, if | begin to recall my life...

828
02:07:05,285 --> 02:07:07,204
...| shall hardly become kinder.

829
02:07:09,039 --> 02:07:13,877
And then, can't you see
how shameful all this is?

830
02:07:31,728 --> 02:07:33,563
To humiliate yourself.

831
02:07:34,564 --> 02:07:37,025
To snivel and to pray.

832
02:07:37,901 --> 02:07:39,653
What's bad about praying?

833
02:07:42,113 --> 02:07:44,074
That's your pride speaking.

834
02:07:46,034 --> 02:07:51,081
Relax. You're just not ready.
That happens.

835
02:07:54,000 --> 02:07:55,752
Perhaps you'll go first?

836
02:08:03,927 --> 02:08:05,262
Me?

837
02:08:16,064 --> 02:08:21,111
Voila! Here we have
the professor's new invention.

838
02:08:22,153 --> 02:08:26,241
A device for testing the human soul.
A soul meter.

839
02:08:26,783 --> 02:08:29,494
It's just a bomb.

840
02:08:29,578 --> 02:08:30,579
What?

841
02:08:32,789 --> 02:08:35,625
- You're joking.
- No.

842
02:08:37,836 --> 02:08:40,046
It's just a 20-kiloton bomb.

843
02:08:41,506 --> 02:08:42,632
What for?

844
02:08:53,602 --> 02:08:57,272
| assembled it with some friends.

845
02:08:59,357 --> 02:09:03,153
With some former colleagues.

846
02:09:07,490 --> 02:09:10,952
This place, evidently,
won't bring anyone happiness.

847
02:09:15,498 --> 02:09:20,086
And if it falls into evil hands...

848
02:09:22,464 --> 02:09:24,633
However, | really don't know now.

849
02:09:26,676 --> 02:09:28,470
Once we had the idea...

850
02:09:31,473 --> 02:09:34,142
...that the Zone should not be destroyed.

851
02:09:35,518 --> 02:09:41,232
Even if it was a miracle,
it was a part of nature.

852
02:09:41,775 --> 02:09:44,361
And in a certain sense, it means hope.

853
02:09:46,655 --> 02:09:51,034
They hid this bomb, but I've found it.

854
02:09:51,409 --> 02:09:54,204
It's an old building, Bunker 4.

855
02:09:59,292 --> 02:10:02,963
Obviously there must be a principle —

856
02:10:04,297 --> 02:10:06,967
never to perform irreversible actions.

857
02:10:07,217 --> 02:10:09,552
| understand that. I'm no maniac.

858
02:10:13,974 --> 02:10:19,437
But as long as this canker
is Open to any scoundrel...

859
02:10:22,148 --> 02:10:23,942
...there can be no rest.

860
02:10:31,783 --> 02:10:34,911
Maybe something inside us won't permit it?

861
02:10:41,418 --> 02:10:44,045
Poor guy, he's made himself a problem.

862
02:11:08,153 --> 02:11:09,320
Give it to me.

863
02:11:24,085 --> 02:11:25,754
Give it to me!

864
02:11:30,592 --> 02:11:32,552
You're an intelligent man.

865
02:11:40,226 --> 02:11:43,313
- What's that for?
- You hypocritical louse!

866
02:11:45,648 --> 02:11:51,362
Why — Why are you doing this to me?

867
02:11:51,446 --> 02:11:54,991
He wants to destroy your hope.

868
02:12:18,181 --> 02:12:21,518
There's nothing else left
to people on Earth.

869
02:12:22,685 --> 02:12:29,442
This is the only place to come to
when all hope is gone.

870
02:12:32,529 --> 02:12:37,867
You have to come here.
Then why destroy hope?

871
02:12:38,535 --> 02:12:40,537
Shut up!

872
02:12:42,747 --> 02:12:46,292
| see through you.

873
02:12:46,376 --> 02:12:49,462
You don't give a damn about others.

874
02:12:49,546 --> 02:12:55,301
You earn your money from our... misery.

875
02:12:55,385 --> 02:12:58,763
It's not even the money. You enjoy this.

876
02:12:58,847 --> 02:13:00,807
Here you're czar and God.

877
02:13:00,890 --> 02:13:05,270
You louse, you decide
who's to die and who's to live.

878
02:13:05,353 --> 02:13:07,689
He chooses, he decides.

879
02:13:09,190 --> 02:13:13,653
| Know why the stalker himself
never enters the Room.

880
02:13:13,736 --> 02:13:19,159
What for?
You're drunk with power out here.

881
02:13:19,242 --> 02:13:21,286
With mystery! With authority!

882
02:13:21,369 --> 02:13:24,581
That's not true. You're wrong.

883
02:13:29,919 --> 02:13:32,422
A stalker is forbidden to enter the Room.

884
02:13:32,505 --> 02:13:36,467
Especially for his own selfish reasons.

885
02:13:37,260 --> 02:13:39,095
Remember Porcupine.

886
02:13:41,890 --> 02:13:44,058
Yes, I'm a louse.

887
02:13:44,142 --> 02:13:47,478
I've never achieved anything,
and | can't do anything here.

888
02:13:49,898 --> 02:13:52,025
| have nothing to give my wife.

889
02:13:53,401 --> 02:13:58,156
| can't have any friends,
but don't deprive me of what's mine.

890
02:13:58,239 --> 02:14:01,910
They took everything from me
behind the barbed wire.

891
02:14:06,122 --> 02:14:08,750
Everything | have is here.

892
02:14:08,833 --> 02:14:11,336
Here, in the Zone.

893
02:14:12,879 --> 02:14:17,717
My happiness, my freedom, dignity.
They're all here.

894
02:14:19,802 --> 02:14:23,598
The people | bring are unhappy like me.

895
02:14:23,681 --> 02:14:27,435
They've nothing left to hope for.
Nobody can help them.

896
02:14:28,728 --> 02:14:34,692
But | can — a louse.
A louse can help them!

897
02:14:37,362 --> 02:14:39,989
| weep for joy because | can help them.

898
02:14:42,075 --> 02:14:43,826
| ask for nothing more.

899
02:15:06,307 --> 02:15:08,017
| don't know. Maybe.

900
02:15:09,102 --> 02:15:11,521
Anyway, forgive me, but —

901
02:15:12,814 --> 02:15:14,774
You're simply one of God's fools.

902
02:15:17,026 --> 02:15:19,696
You've no conception
of what's happening here.

903
02:15:23,992 --> 02:15:27,203
Why do you think Porcupine
hanged himself?

904
02:15:27,537 --> 02:15:34,127
He came to the Zone for profit,
and his brother died for money.

905
02:15:34,210 --> 02:15:38,131
| understand that,
but why did he hang himself?

906
02:15:38,214 --> 02:15:42,218
Why didn't he come back?
Not for money, but for his brother.

907
02:15:43,720 --> 02:15:45,471
Is that how he repented?

908
02:15:45,555 --> 02:15:49,976
He wanted to.
But within a few days, he hanged himself.

909
02:15:50,059 --> 02:15:56,065
He realized that it is one's
most secret desire that is granted here.

910
02:16:04,574 --> 02:16:06,868
What are you yelling about?

911
02:16:15,168 --> 02:16:19,839
What comes true here is that which
reflects the essence of your nature.

912
02:16:19,922 --> 02:16:23,009
It is within you. It governs you.

913
02:16:23,092 --> 02:16:26,596
Yet you are ignorant of it.

914
02:16:26,679 --> 02:16:31,351
You've understood nothing.
Greed didn't do Porcupine in.

915
02:16:31,434 --> 02:16:35,146
He crawled on his knees
to plead for his brother,

916
02:16:35,229 --> 02:16:37,482
but he got a pile of money.

917
02:16:37,565 --> 02:16:40,443
He couldn't get anything else.

918
02:16:41,152 --> 02:16:44,697
Porcupine was given the essence
of his true nature.

919
02:16:44,781 --> 02:16:49,702
Conscience and soul-searching
were all invented by the mind.

920
02:16:49,786 --> 02:16:51,913
When he realized all that,
he hanged himself.

921
02:16:56,834 --> 02:16:58,586
| won't go into your Room.

922
02:17:00,671 --> 02:17:05,927
| don't want to pour the filth in my soul
onto anyone's head —

923
02:17:06,010 --> 02:17:08,304
even yours —

924
02:17:08,388 --> 02:17:10,556
and then hang myself as Porcupine did.

925
02:17:12,141 --> 02:17:17,188
Better to stay grunting
in my stinking private villa.

926
02:17:19,607 --> 02:17:25,196
You're a bad judge of human nature

927
02:17:25,279 --> 02:17:27,865
if you bring people like me into the Zone.

928
02:17:35,873 --> 02:17:43,256
How did you learn
that this miracle actually exists?

929
02:17:44,715 --> 02:17:49,429
Who told you that desires
really come true here?

930
02:17:51,722 --> 02:17:56,352
Do you know one man
who was made happy here?

931
02:17:57,645 --> 02:17:59,605
Perhaps Porcupine?

932
02:18:04,485 --> 02:18:09,115
And who told you about the Zone,

933
02:18:09,198 --> 02:18:12,785
about Porcupine, about this Room?

934
02:18:14,370 --> 02:18:15,538
He did.

935
02:19:20,561 --> 02:19:22,813
| don't understand anything at all.

936
02:19:24,440 --> 02:19:26,943
What's the sense in coming here?

937
02:20:50,443 --> 02:20:51,944
It's so still.

938
02:20:53,529 --> 02:20:55,031
Can you hear it?

939
02:21:00,369 --> 02:21:03,497
Suppose | chuck it all in...

940
02:21:05,374 --> 02:21:09,795
...get my wife and Monkey
and come here to live...

941
02:21:13,549 --> 02:21:14,884
... forever.

942
02:21:17,386 --> 02:21:18,888
There's nobody here.

943
02:21:20,222 --> 02:21:22,058
No one will hurt them.

944
02:25:37,146 --> 02:25:38,856
You came back.

945
02:25:44,904 --> 02:25:46,655
Where did the dog come from?

946
02:25:48,157 --> 02:25:52,161
It tagged along. Don't chase it away.

947
02:26:09,511 --> 02:26:12,640
Well, shall we go?

948
02:26:13,599 --> 02:26:15,351
Monkey's waiting.

949
02:26:19,229 --> 02:26:20,564
Are we going?

950
02:26:34,995 --> 02:26:36,997
Does anybody want a dog?

951
02:26:40,376 --> 02:26:42,711
I've got five already.

952
02:26:52,888 --> 02:26:55,391
So you like dogs?

953
02:26:55,975 --> 02:26:57,476
What?

954
02:26:57,559 --> 02:26:58,894
That's good.

955
02:27:04,775 --> 02:27:07,069
All right, let's go.

956
02:30:10,127 --> 02:30:12,129
If you only knew how tired | am.

957
02:30:14,173 --> 02:30:15,966
Only God knows.

958
02:30:18,051 --> 02:30:21,138
They still call themselves
the intelligentsia.

959
02:30:21,221 --> 02:30:24,808
Writers! Scientists!
- Calm down.

960
02:30:24,892 --> 02:30:27,436
They don't believe in anything.

961
02:30:27,519 --> 02:30:32,524
Their capacity for faith has atrophied —

962
02:30:32,608 --> 02:30:34,401
- Calm yourself.
- ...through lack of use.

963
02:30:36,153 --> 02:30:40,115
Stop it. Come, lie down. Don't worry.

964
02:30:40,199 --> 02:30:44,745
It's damp. You can't stay here.

965
02:30:48,540 --> 02:30:50,042
Take it off.

966
02:32:01,321 --> 02:32:03,240
My God, what kind people are they?

967
02:32:03,323 --> 02:32:07,619
Calm down. It isn't their fault.

968
02:32:07,703 --> 02:32:10,414
They should be pitied, not abused.

969
02:32:10,497 --> 02:32:12,833
Their eyes are blank.

970
02:32:25,721 --> 02:32:29,266
They're thinking
how not to sell themselves cheap,

971
02:32:29,349 --> 02:32:34,938
how to get paid
for every breath they take.

972
02:32:38,108 --> 02:32:42,612
They know they were born
to "be someone,' to be an elite!

973
02:32:45,532 --> 02:32:47,242
They say, "You live but once."

974
02:32:49,578 --> 02:32:52,331
How can such people believe
in anything at all?

975
02:32:53,707 --> 02:32:55,417
Relax now.

976
02:32:55,500 --> 02:32:59,588
Try to get some sleep.

977
02:33:00,630 --> 02:33:02,132
Go to sleep.

978
02:33:05,594 --> 02:33:09,222
Nobody believes. Not only those two.

979
02:33:10,599 --> 02:33:11,933
Nobody.

980
02:33:12,434 --> 02:33:14,186
Who shall | take there?

981
02:33:18,440 --> 02:33:20,776
Oh, Lord.

982
02:33:20,859 --> 02:33:22,361
The most terrible thing...

983
02:33:24,905 --> 02:33:31,078
...1S that nobody needs that Room
and all my efforts are in vain.

984
02:33:32,454 --> 02:33:35,415
Why do you say that? Don't.

985
02:33:41,797 --> 02:33:43,840
I'll never go there again with anyone.

986
02:33:47,177 --> 02:33:51,598
If you want, I'll go there with you.
Do you want that?

987
02:33:54,059 --> 02:33:56,520
Do you think I've nothing to ask for?

988
02:34:01,608 --> 02:34:02,818
No.

989
02:34:06,655 --> 02:34:09,032
You mustn't.
- Why?

990
02:34:12,327 --> 02:34:13,537
No.

991
02:34:18,708 --> 02:34:22,421
What if you fail, too?

992
02:34:58,707 --> 02:35:01,543
You know, Mama was very opposed to it.

993
02:35:03,879 --> 02:35:08,508
You've probably already guessed
that he's one of God's fools.

994
02:35:11,470 --> 02:35:13,805
Everyone around here used to laugh at him.

995
02:35:13,889 --> 02:35:16,683
He was such a wretched muddler.

996
02:35:19,311 --> 02:35:21,563
Mama used to Say,

997
02:35:21,646 --> 02:35:26,026
"He's a stalker, a marked man,
an eternal jailbird.

998
02:35:26,109 --> 02:35:28,987
Remember the kind of children
stalkers have."

999
02:35:29,070 --> 02:35:31,948
| didn't even argue.

1000
02:35:34,868 --> 02:35:37,245
| Knew all about it —

1001
02:35:37,329 --> 02:35:43,126
that he was a marked man, a jailbird,
about the kids.

1002
02:35:46,963 --> 02:35:49,007
Only what could | do?

1003
02:35:49,090 --> 02:35:51,801
| was sure I'd be happy with him.

1004
02:35:54,387 --> 02:35:56,556
| knew there'd be a lot of sorrow.

1005
02:35:58,183 --> 02:36:03,104
But I'd rather know
bittersweet happiness...

1006
02:36:04,773 --> 02:36:06,608
... than a gray, uneventtul life.

1007
02:36:11,613 --> 02:36:15,033
Perhaps | invented all this later.

1008
02:36:24,751 --> 02:36:29,673
But when he came up to me and said,
"Come with me," | went.

1009
02:36:31,299 --> 02:36:34,010
And I've never regretted it.

1010
02:36:37,806 --> 02:36:39,140
Never.

1011
02:36:41,893 --> 02:36:45,021
There was a lot of grief

1012
02:36:45,105 --> 02:36:47,440
and fear and pain.

1013
02:36:47,524 --> 02:36:51,152
But I've never regretted it
nor envied anyone.

1014
02:36:53,238 --> 02:36:55,156
It's just fate.

1015
02:36:56,783 --> 02:36:59,202
It's life. It's us.

1016
02:37:04,666 --> 02:37:08,420
And if there were no sorrow in our lives,
it wouldn't be better.

1017
02:37:10,130 --> 02:37:11,715
It would be worse.

1018
02:37:14,426 --> 02:37:19,222
Because then
there would be no happiness either.

1019
02:37:21,766 --> 02:37:24,144
And there'd be no hope.

1020
02:37:27,480 --> 02:37:28,690
SO...

1021
02:38:15,153 --> 02:38:18,782
/ love those eyes of yours, my friend,

1022
02:38:18,865 --> 02:38:23,495
Their sparkling, tlashing, tlery wonder;

1023
02:38:23,578 --> 02:38:27,332
When suddenly those lids ascend,

1024
02:38:27,415 --> 02:38:30,835
Then lightning rips the sky asunder,

1025
02:38:30,919 --> 02:38:35,006
You swiftly glance, and there's an end,

1026
02:38:35,090 --> 02:38:38,677
There's greater charm, though, to admire

1027
02:38:38,760 --> 02:38:42,222
When lowered are those eyes divine

1028
02:38:42,305 --> 02:38:45,850
In moments kissed by passion's fire;

1029
02:38:45,934 --> 02:38:50,021
When through the downcast lashes shine

1030
02:38:50,105 --> 02:38:56,611
The smoldering embers of desire...

